To make the Ant Design <Modal> responsive in height and width, you can adapt it dynamically based on the viewport. Here's how to do it:

✅ Recommended Solution:

  1. Use width: "90vw" instead of a fixed value like 1200
    This sets the modal width to 90% of the viewport width.

  2. Use maxWidth to prevent it from getting too wide on large screens

  3. Control height via bodyStyle using maxHeight: "80vh" and overflowY: "auto"
    This ensures the modal content is scrollable if it exceeds the viewport height.

🔧 Updated Code:

jsx
<Modal
    title={null}
    open={isAdviseModalVisible}
    onCancel={handleAdviseCancel}
    width="90vw"
    style={{ maxWidth: 1200 }}
    footer={null}
    centered
    destroyOnClose
    className="luxury-modal"
    bodyStyle={{
        padding: 0,
        maxHeight: '80vh',
        overflowY: 'auto',
        overflowX: 'hidden',
        boxShadow: '0 24px 80px rgba(0,0,0,0.15)',
    }}
>

✅ Explanation:

  • width: "90vw": Makes the modal 90% of the viewport width.

  • maxWidth: 1200: Prevents the modal from becoming too wide on very large screens.

  • maxHeight: '80vh': Restricts the modal height to 80% of the viewport height.

  • overflowY: 'auto': Adds scroll if the content overflows.

Yes, your current code structure can be used to handle Excel or PDF uploads via Supabase Storage — but with a few important notes:

✅ What Already Works

  • Supabase Storage supports any file type, not just images.

  • Your function uploadImage actually uploads any file — despite the name.

  • So, .xlsx, .xls, .pdf, .docx, .csv, etc. are all valid.

🛠️ What You Should Change or Improve

1. Rename uploadImage to uploadFile (Optional but recommended for clarity)

ts
export const uploadFile = async (file: File): Promise<string> => {
    const timestamp = Date.now();
    const fileExt = file.name.split('.').pop();
    const filePath = `${timestamp}_${file.name}`;

    const { error } = await supabase.storage
        .from('uploads')
        .upload(filePath, file);

    if (error) {
        throw new Error(`Upload failed: ${error.message}`);
    }

    return filePath;
};

🔁 Also update the function calls accordingly.

If you're doing validation before upload, check the MIME type:

  throw new Error('Only PDF and Excel files are allowed');

The uploaded Excel file contains a sheet named "Table 1" with a structured curriculum plan, but the first few rows are header or metadata rows.

The relevant course data seems to start after a few lines, possibly after the row with headers like:

✅ Goal

We’ll now create a React TypeScript page that:

  1. Accepts Excel file upload (.xlsx)

  2. Parses it using xlsx npm package

  3. Extracts course data (like code, title, credits)

  4. Displays it in a table

📦 Install Required Package

Install xlsx:

bash
npm install xlsx

📄 React TypeScript Page Example

tsx
// ExcelUpload.tsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import * as XLSX from 'xlsx';

interface Course {
  code: string;
  title: string;
  credits: number;
  prerequisites: string;
  corequisites: string;
}

const ExcelUpload: React.FC = () => {
  const [courses, setCourses] = useState<Course[]>([]);

  const handleFileUpload = async (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
    const file = e.target.files?.[0];
    if (!file) return;

    const data = await file.arrayBuffer();
    const workbook = XLSX.read(data, { type: 'array' });
    const sheet = workbook.Sheets[workbook.SheetNames[0]];

    const raw = XLSX.utils.sheet_to_json(sheet, { header: 1 }) as string[][];

    // Find the index of the actual header row
    const headerIndex = raw.findIndex(row =>
      row.includes("Code") && row.includes("Title") && row.includes("Credits")
    );

    const rows = raw.slice(headerIndex + 1);

    const extracted: Course[] = rows
      .filter(row => row.length >= 3 && row[0]) // filter valid rows
      .map(row => ({
        code: row[0]?.toString().trim(),
        title: row[1]?.toString().trim(),
        credits: Number(row[2]),
        prerequisites: row[3]?.toString().trim() || '',
        corequisites: row[4]?.toString().trim() || '',
      }));

    setCourses(extracted);
  };

  return (
    <div className="p-4">
      <h2 className="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Upload Excel File</h2>
      <input
        type="file"
        accept=".xlsx, .xls"
        onChange={handleFileUpload}
        className="mb-4"
      />

      {courses.length > 0 && (
        <table className="w-full table-auto border-collapse border border-gray-300">
          <thead>
            <tr className="bg-gray-100">
              <th className="border p-2">Code</th>
              <th className="border p-2">Title</th>
              <th className="border p-2">Credits</th>
              <th className="border p-2">Prerequisites</th>
              <th className="border p-2">Corequisites</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {courses.map((course, index) => (
              <tr key={index}>
                <td className="border p-2">{course.code}</td>
                <td className="border p-2">{course.title}</td>
                <td className="border p-2">{course.credits}</td>
                <td className="border p-2">{course.prerequisites}</td>
                <td className="border p-2">{course.corequisites}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};

export default ExcelUpload;

✅ Notes

  • This reads only the first sheet.

  • The header row (Code, Title, etc.) is dynamically detected.

  • The UI is basic but styled for readability.

Let me know if you want it integrated into Ant Design components or support for multiple sheets/sections (like Year/Semester separation).

tsx
// ExcelUpload.tsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import * as XLSX from 'xlsx';

interface Course {
  code: string;
  title: string;
  credits: number;
  prerequisites: string[];
  corequisites: string[];
}

const ExcelUpload: React.FC = () => {
  const [courses, setCourses] = useState<Course[]>([]);

  const handleFileUpload = async (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
    const file = e.target.files?.[0];
    if (!file) return;

    const data = await file.arrayBuffer();
    const workbook = XLSX.read(data, { type: 'array' });
    const sheet = workbook.Sheets[workbook.SheetNames[0]];
    const raw = XLSX.utils.sheet_to_json<string[][]>(sheet, { header: 1 });

    // locate header row dynamically
    const headerIndex = raw.findIndex(row =>
      row.includes("Code") && row.includes("Title") && row.includes("Credits")
    );
    const rows = raw.slice(headerIndex + 1);

    const extracted: Course[] = rows
      .filter(row => row[0]) // must have a code
      .map(row => {
        // helper: split on commas or semicolons, trim, and drop empties
        const splitList = (cell?: string | number): string[] => {
          if (!cell) return [];
          return cell
            .toString()
            .split(/[,;]+/)
            .map(s => s.trim())
            .filter(Boolean);
        };

        return {
          code: row[0].toString().trim(),
          title: row[1]?.toString().trim() || '',
          credits: Number(row[2] || 0),
          prerequisites: splitList(row[3]),
          corequisites: splitList(row[4]),
        };
      });

    setCourses(extracted);
  };

  return (
    <div className="p-4">
      <h2 className="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Upload Excel File</h2>
      <input
        type="file"
        accept=".xlsx, .xls"
        onChange={handleFileUpload}
        className="mb-4"
      />

      {courses.length > 0 && (
        <table className="w-full table-auto border-collapse border border-gray-300">
          <thead>
            <tr className="bg-gray-100">
              <th className="border p-2">Code</th>
              <th className="border p-2">Title</th>
              <th className="border p-2">Credits</th>
              <th className="border p-2">Prerequisites</th>
              <th className="border p-2">Corequisites</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {courses.map((course, i) => (
              <tr key={i}>
                <td className="border p-2">{course.code}</td>
                <td className="border p-2">{course.title}</td>
                <td className="border p-2">{course.credits}</td>
                <td className="border p-2">
                  {course.prerequisites.join(', ')}
                </td>
                <td className="border p-2">
                  {course.corequisites.join(', ')}
                </td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};

export default ExcelUpload;

Key changes:

  • Course.prerequisites and .corequisites are now string[].

  • After reading each row, we split the raw cell on commas/semicolons into an array, trimming out empties.

  • The sample JSON above mirrors exactly how your React state (courses) will look.

Here’s a revised set of TypeScript interfaces under the top‑level name PlanOfStudy, reflecting your requirements:

ts
// types/planOfStudy.ts

/** Allowed course “types” */
export type CourseType =
  | 'Core'
  | 'Major'
  | 'Major Elective'
  | 'General Elective'
  | 'General Requirement';

/** Allowed semester offerings */
export type Semester =
  | 'Fall'
  | 'Spring'
  | 'Summer'
  | 'Fall-Spring'
  | 'Fall-Summer'
  | 'Spring-Summer'
  | 'Fall-Spring-Summer';

/** A single course entry in the plan */
export interface Course {
  code: string;
  title: string;
  credits: number;
  type: CourseType;
  semesters: Semester;
}

/** Junction record linking a course to its prereqs & coreqs */
export interface CourseLink {
  /** the course itself */
  courseId: string;
  /** a prerequisite course code (empty if none) */
  coursePre?: string;
  /** a corequisite course code (empty if none) */
  courseCo?: string;
}

/** The full “plan of study” payload */
export interface PlanOfStudy {
  departmentId: number;
  departmentName: string;
  courses: Course[];
  /** each object links one course to one prereq or coreq */
  prerequisitesCorequisites: CourseLink[];
}

  • Course now includes type (your 5 categories) and semesters (any of the specified strings).

  • CourseLink is the junction array item, with optional coursePre / courseCo.

  • PlanOfStudy wraps everything plus department info.

ChatGPT said:

What you’re seeing is the interplay of two things:

  1. Literal "undefined" strings (when your code actually received the string "undefined"),

  2. Nullish coalescing (?? null) turning truly missing elements into null.

1. Where did "undefined" come from?

If you ever passed the string "undefined" into processLinks – for example because you did something like:

ts
const codesCo = course.courseCo + ''; // where courseCo was actually `undefined`
processLinks(codesPre, codesCo);

then codesCo becomes the four‑character string "undefined", so

ts
const coArray = codesCo.split('-');
// → ['undefined']

and later

ts
coArray[j]  // is the string "undefined"

Because "undefined" is not null or undefined as far as ?? is concerned, it stays a string.

2. Where did the null come from?

When you split a shorter array with a loop like

ts
for (let i = 0, j = 0; i < preArray.length || j < coArray.length; i++, j++) {
  links.push({
    courseId: currentCourseId,
    coursePre: preArray[i] ?? null,
    courseCo:  coArray[j] ?? null,
  });
}

any index j that’s beyond coArray.length – 1 yields coArray[j] === undefined. The ?? null then turns that undefined into null.

Summing up

  • String "undefined" entries happen when your input was literally the string "undefined".

  • null entries happen when you ran off the end of the split array and your ?? null kicked in.

How to fix it

Before you split, normalize codesCo (and codesPre) so you never split the string "undefined":

ts
const safeSplit = (s?: string) =>
  (s ?? '')   // if s is null or undefined, use empty string
    .split('-')
    .filter(item => item && item !== 'undefined'); // drop empty or literal "undefined"

const processLinks = (codesPre?: string, codesCo?: string) => {
  const preArray = safeSplit(codesPre);
  const coArray  = safeSplit(codesCo);

  for (let i = 0, j = 0; i < preArray.length || j < coArray.length; i++, j++) {
    const pre = preArray[i] ?? null;
    const co  = coArray[j]  ?? null;

    // only push if there’s something real
    if (pre || co) {
      links.push({
        courseId:    currentCourseId,
        coursePre:   pre,
        courseCo:    co,
      });
    }
  }
};

  • s ?? '' ensures you never split on undefined or null.

  • .filter(... !== 'undefined') drops any literal "undefined" tokens.

  • You’ll end up with only real course‑ID strings or null at missing positions.

You don’t actually want to stick an array of strings into AntD’s columns prop — you need an array of column definitions. The easiest pattern is:

  1. Keep your raw header row (raw[2]) in state as string[].

  2. Derive your ColumnsType by mapping those strings into objects of shape { title, dataIndex, key }.

Here’s a snippet that shows how:

tsx
import React, { useState, useMemo } from 'react';
import { Table } from 'antd';
import type { ColumnsType } from 'antd/es/table';

interface Course {
  code: string;
  title: string;
  credits: number;
  prerequisites: string;
  corequisites: string;
  type: string;
  semester: string;
}

const Example: React.FC = () => {
  const [columnsRaw, setColumnsRaw] = useState<string[]>([]);
  const [dataRaw, setDataRaw]       = useState<Course[]>([]);
  const [loading, setLoading]       = useState(false);

  // whenever you read your Excel `raw`:
  //   setColumnsRaw(raw[2]);        // row 2 is your header row
  //   setDataRaw(raw.slice(3));     // row 3+ is your data

  // derive AntD columns from the raw header titles:
  const columns = useMemo<ColumnsType<Course>>(() => {
    return columnsRaw.map(header => {
      // normalize your dataIndex/key so it matches your Course keys:
      const dataIndex = header.trim().toLowerCase() as keyof Course;

      return {
        title:    header,
        dataIndex,
        key:      dataIndex,
        // you can also add sorter, render, width, etc. here
      };
    });
  }, [columnsRaw]);

  return (
    <Table<Course>
      rowKey="code"
      loading={loading}
      dataSource={dataRaw}
      columns={columns}
      pagination={{ pageSize: 10 }}
    />
  );
};

What’s happening here?

  • columnsRaw: string[] holds your Excel header row, e.g.
    ["Code", "Title", "Credits", "Prerequisites", "Corequisites", "type", "Semester"].

  • useMemo maps each header into an AntD column definition:

    ts
    {
  title: header,              // what shows in the table header
  dataIndex: header.toLowerCase(), // must match your data object’s key
  key: header.toLowerCase(),
}

  • Make sure that your dataRaw objects use those exact keys (code, title, credits, prerequisites, corequisites, type, semester) so that the table can pick up each cell’s value automatically.

With this pattern you never have to assert as ColumnsType — the types line up automatically.

  margin-bottom: 8px;
}

/* Left‐aligned (default) bubble */
.message-left {
  justify-content: flex-start;
}

.message-left .bubble {
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
  color: #000;
  border-radius: 16px;
  padding: 8px 12px;
  max-width: 60%;
}

/* Right‐aligned “WhatsApp‐green” bubble */
.message-right {
  justify-content: flex-end;
}

.message-right .bubble {
  background-color: #dcf8c6; /* WhatsApp light green */
  color: #000;
  border-radius: 16px;
  padding: 8px 12px;
  max-width: 60%;
}

2. Use it in your component

tsx
import React from 'react';
import './Chat.css';

type Message = {
  id: string;
  text: string;
  isMine: boolean;  // true = right, false = left
};

export const ChatBubble: React.FC<{ message: Message }> = ({ message }) => {
  const wrapperClass = message.isMine ? 'message-right' : 'message-left';

  return (
    <div className={`message-container ${wrapperClass}`}>
      <div className="bubble">
        {message.text}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

3. Example usage

tsx
const messages: Message[] = [
  { id: '1', text: 'Hey, how are you?', isMine: false },
  { id: '2', text: 'I’m good, thanks! You?', isMine: true },
  { id: '3', text: 'Doing great—thanks for asking!', isMine: false },
];

export const ChatWindow = () => (
  <div>
    {messages.map(m => (
      <ChatBubble key={m.id} message={m} />
    ))}
  </div>
);

That will render left‑aligned gray bubbles for incoming messages, and right‑aligned light‑green WhatsApp‑style bubbles for your own messages. Feel free to tweak colors, border‑radii or padding to taste!
